A polyfill is a piece of code (usually JavaScript on the Web) used to provide modern functionality on older browsers that do not natively support it.
For example, a polyfill could be used to mimic the functionality of an HTML Canvas element on Microsoft Internet Explorer 7 using a Silverlight plugin, or mimic support for CSS rem units, or text-shadow, or what have you.

Remy Sharp coined the term “polyfill”, and you can refer to his original post for more information on its origin.
In the broadest sense, a polyfill is a piece of code that provides the technology that you, the developer, expect the browser to provide natively.

If the dimensions of two arrays are dissimilar, element-to-element operations are not possible. The smaller array is broadcast to the size of the larger array so that they have compatible shapes.

As they approached the checkpoint, George Washington was asked to remove his shoes and place them in a bin. He complied without complaint, but couldn't help but feel a bit embarrassed at having to do so in front of his fellow Founding Fathers.
Next up was John Adams, who was asked to empty his pockets and put his belongings in a tray. He did so, but not before making a snide remark about how ridiculous it was that he had to go through such a process just to get on a plane.
Thomas Jefferson was next, and he too had to remove his shoes and empty his pockets. However, he also had to undergo a full body scan, which he found to be quite invasive. He couldn't help but wonder if this was really necessary, especially since he was a Founding Father and not a terrorist.

The other Founding Fathers watched in amazement as Franklin argued with the TSA agent. They had never seen him so passionate about anything before.

As they boarded the plane, they couldn't help but wonder what the future held for air travel. Would it always be this way, with everyone having to go through such a rigorous screening process? Or would things eventually change?

Semantic search is a search or a question or an action that produces meaningful results, even when the retrieved items contain none of the query terms, or the search involves no query text at all.
For example, when you ask Google or Bing or Yahoo! "Who is the President of the United States", the page that contains the answer (a Wikipedia page) does not contain the terms "Who", "is", or "the". The search engine understands that you are looking for a person, and that "President of the United States" is a title of a person, and based on the capitalization of the title, that it is a title of a person about which there is a Wikipedia page. The search engine has to understand that the result the user is looking for is not necessarily a page with the best text match, but rather a page with the answer to the question.

6. Select the "Appear" animation and then click on the "Trigger" button.
7. Select the "On Click of" option and then select the WebBrowser control from the list of objects.
8. Click "OK" to save the trigger.

    import csv
    from Bio import SeqIO
    from Levenshtein import distance
    
    # Read in the FASTQ file containing the reads
    reads = list(SeqIO.parse("reads.fastq", "fastq"))
    
    # Read in the text file containing the barcodes
    with open("barcodes.txt") as f:
        barcodes = [line.strip() for line in f]
    
    # Initialize a dictionary to store the barcode assignments
    assignments = {}
    
    # Loop through each read
    for read in reads:
        # Calculate the Levenshtein distance between the read and each barcode
        distances = [distance(read.seq, barcode) for barcode in barcodes]
        
        # Find the index of the minimum distance
        min_index = distances.index(min(distances))
        
        # Assign the read to the corresponding barcode
        assignments[read.id] = barcodes[min_index]
    
    # Write the barcode assignments to a CSV file
    with open("assignments.csv", "w") as f:
        writer = csv.writer(f)
        writer.writerow(["Read ID", "Barcode"])
        for read_id, barcode in assignments.items():
            writer.writerow([read_id, barcode])
